tforms. At a time when Black women are depicted as more ugly, deficient, hypersexual, and unhealthy than their non-Black counterparts, Bailey explores how Black women have bravely used social-media platforms to confront misogynoir in a number of courageous—and, most importantly, effective—ways. Focusing on queer and trans Black women, she shows us the importance of carving out digital spaces, where communities are built around queer Black webshows and hashtags like #GirlsLikeUs. Bailey shows how Black women actively reimagine the world by engaging in powerful forms of digital resistance at a time when anti-Black misogyny is thriving on social media. A groundbreaking work, Misogynoir Transformed highlights Black women’s remarkable efforts to disrupt mainstream narratives, subvert negative stereotypes, and reclaim their lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American women in popular culturezUnited States. 0aAfrican American women in social media. 0aAfrican American womenxSocial conditions. 0aMisogynoirzUnited States. 0aMisogynyzUnited States. 0aSocial mediazUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  a#FreeCeCe.  a#GirlsLikeUs.  a#RuinABlackGirlsMonday.  a#YourSlipIsShowing.  a195 Lewis.  aAdultification.  aBetween Women.  aBlack Girls.  aBlack queer women.  aBlack trans women.  aBlack women.  aCeCe McDonald.  aDefensive Digital Alchemy.  aDigital Alchemy.  aDrag.  aGenerative Digital Alchemy.  aHarm Reduction.  aHealth.  aJanet Mock.  aMasculinity.  aNap Ministry.  aNetworks.  aNonbinary femmes.  aQueer.  aReading.  aRedefining Realness.  aRelationships.  aSkye’s The Limit.  aSocial Media Platforms.  aSocial Media.  aStereotypes.  aTherapy.  aTrans.  aTransformation.  aTransformative Justice.  aTumblr.  aTwi